Foot-and-mouth disease, Namibia
-------------------------------
Information received on (and dated) 8 Aug 2013 from Dr Albertina Shilongo, Chief Veterinarian, Epidemiology, Import and Export Control and Training, Directorate of Veterinary Services, Ministry of Agriculture, Water & Forestry, Windhoek, Namibia

Summary
Report type: immediate notification
Date of start of the event: 4 Aug 2013
Date of pre-confirmation of the event: 5 Aug 2013
Report date: 8 Aug 2013
Date submitted to OIE: 8 Aug 2013
Reason for notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 20 Mar 2012
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: Foot and mouth disease virus
Serotype: pending
Nature of diagnosis: clinical
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country

New outbreaks
Summary of outbreaks
Total outbreaks: 1
Outbreak Location: Caprivi (Ivilivinzi, Kabbe Constituency, Caprivi)
Total animals affected
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle / 761 / 15 / 0 / 0 / 0

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: Contact with wild species
Epidemiological comments: the outbreak has occurred in the foot-and-mouth disease infected zone where there are free roaming wild African buffaloes which are long term reservoirs of the FMD virus.

Note by the OIE Animal Health Information Department: this event is outside the officially recognized free zone and does not change the FMD free zone status of Namibia.

Control measures
Measures applied: quarantine, movement control inside the country, screening, vaccination in response to the outbreak(s), disinfection of infected premises/establishment(s), dipping/spraying, no treatment of affected animals.
Measures to be applied: no other measures.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The notification includes an interactive map showing the location of the outbreak in Eastern Caprivi, on the border with Botswana and adjacent to the territories of Zambia and Zimbabwe.

Typing of the causative virus strain is anticipated (all 3 SAT types are endemic in the African buffalo population).

Namibia's page in the WRLFMD (Pirbright) website, which includes data from 1949 to the present, is accessible at http://www.wrlfmd.org/fmd_genotyping/africa/nmb.htm. - Mod.AS]
